docs.abstract: Ineffective monetary policy, scant action from governments, and fear of a leadership void is raising alarm about the pandemic’s economic shock.
docs.snippet: Ineffective monetary policy, scant action from governments, and fear of a leadership void is raising alarm about the pandemic’s economic shock.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last time the world seized with panic over an economic catastrophe, those given the job of limiting the damage knew what to do. The global financial crisis of 2008 presented a textbook case of what happens when people lose faith in the banking system all at once. World leaders could rely on lessons gleaned from history to forge a plan: They flooded the markets with money and waited for calm to return.

headline.main: Markets Plunge. Economies Stall. Panic Spreads. It All Feels Very 2008.
headline.print_headline: This Panic, Unlike 2008’s, Defies the Policy Playbook
